      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "75cd49f3b09ba675",
      "text": "LUHMANN, Niklas, 2018. Systemtheorie der Gesellschaft. 2. Aufl. Berlin: Suhrkamp. ISBN 978-3-518-58705-8, p. 336–337."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a2f0f328e02f2848",
      "text": "Evolution is therefore only possible by the fact that the share of the assumed and insofar effective communications in the total of occurring intelligible communications is variable. For interaction systems, a proportion that is not too low is likely to be a condition for the continuation of interaction. In this respect interaction systems tend to keep the share of non-effective communication small. For social systems capable of evolution - and in this respect again the discussed level differentiation is significant - this tendency does not apply without further ado. It even seems to be reversible within certain limits. On the level of social evolution the difference between comprehensible and assumed communication marks the difference of the mechanisms for variation and for selection. The larger the difference, the larger the range of selection and thus the selectivity of evolutionary selection (which is something quite different from the selectivity of individual communication and the probability of its adoption)."
    }
